-- BHP,  Eldorado, Newcrest, Rio, Santos, Woodside: Australian, N.Z. Stocks
-- Shani Raja
-- 2010-07-12T06:53:27Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-12/asx-bhp-newcrest-rio-santos-sigma-woodside-australian-n-z-stocks.html

          
          
             Australia’s  S&P/ASX 200 Index  rose
0.3 percent to 4,409.90 at the close of trading in Sydney. New
Zealand’s  NZX 50 Index  climbed 0.2 percent to 3,012.03 in
Wellington.  
 The following were among the most active shares in the
market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company
names.  
 Mining shares: Three-month delivery copper fell as much as
0.8 percent to $6,707.25 a metric ton on the London Metal
Exchange and traded $6,715 at 1:30 p.m. in Shanghai.  
 BHP Billiton  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining company,
increased 0.5 percent to A$38.61 in Sydney. BHP said in an
emailed statement there was no impact to its operations in Chile
after an earthquake in the region.  
 Rio Tinto Group  (RIO AU), the world’s third-largest mining
company, gained 1 percent to A$68.77. Rio Tinto is inviting bids
of as much as $75 million for its Chapudi coal exploration
assets in South Africa, the Independent on Sunday reported,
citing a person it said was close to the company.  
 Oil companies: Crude for August delivery dropped as much as
0.6 percent to $75.60 a barrel on the New York Mercantile
Exchange. The contract was at $75.64 at 2:22 p.m. Singapore time.  
 Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
largest oil and gas producer, rose 0.1 percent to A$42.57. Rival
 Santos Ltd.  (STO AU) climbed 0.8 percent to A$14.11. Santos had
its stock rating raised to “buy” from “neutral” by analysts
led by  Gordon Ramsay  at UBS AG.  
 Gold producers: Gold for immediate delivery decreased 0.2
percent to $1,209.40 an ounce at 12:46 p.m. in Singapore.
Futures for August delivery in New York were little changed at
$1,209 an ounce.  
 Newcrest Mining Ltd.  (NCM AU), Australia’s biggest gold
producer, increased 2 percent to A$34.98. Rival  Eldorado Gold
Corp.  (EAU AU) rose 5.9 percent to A$19.79.  St. Barbara Ltd. 
(SBM AU) climbed 6.2 percent to 34.5 Australian cents.  
 Grange Resources Ltd.  (GRR AU) gained 5.1 percent to 52
Australian cents. The nation’s largest iron-ore-pellet producer
is seeking debt funding from China to help finance a A$1.8
billion ($1.6 billion) iron-ore mine in Western Australia.  
 Kangaroo Resources Ltd.  (KRL AU) surged 16 percent to 14.5
Australian cents. The mine developer, which has assets in
Indonesia, hired Macquarie Group Ltd. to help manage a possible
sale of the GPK coal project in East Kalimantan province.  
 OceanaGold Corp.  (OGC AU) increased 9.6 percent to A$3.42,
its biggest gain since May 27, after results of exploration at
its Frasers mine on New Zealand’s South Island added to signs of
increased gold reserves.  
